Ahmed Deedat inspired a new generation of Muslim debaters and scholars who followed in his footsteps, including Zakir Naik. His bold and unapologetic style of interfaith engagement was admired by many Muslims, especially in regions where they faced missionary pressure.

However, his methods were not without criticism. Some accused him of being too confrontational and lacking theological nuance. Others, including Christian scholars, argued that his interpretation of the Bible was selective and polemical. Despite these criticisms, his impact on Islamic apologetics remains significant.

### Later Years and Illness

In 1996, Ahmed Deedat suffered a severe stroke that left him paralyzed from the neck down and unable to speak, though his mind remained alert. He spent the last nine years of his life in bed, communicating only through eye movements using a special system developed by his family and caretakers.

Even during this period, he remained mentally active, guiding the IPCI and receiving visitors from all over the world.

### Death and Legacy

Ahmed Deedat passed away on August 8, 2005, at the age of 87, in Verulam, South Africa. His funeral was attended by thousands, and tributes poured in from across the globe.

His legacy continues through the IPCI and the countless recordings, books, and lectures that remain widely available. He is remembered as a pioneering figure in Islamic da’wah and a bold voice in interfaith dialogue, especially in the context of the 20th century's religious discourse.

